16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiscussions about the meaning of terrorism are enduring in everyday language, government policy, news reporting, and international politics. And disagreements about both the definition and the class of violent events that constitute terrorism contribute to the difficulty of formulating effective responses aimed at the prevention and management of the threat of terrorism and the development of counterterrorism policies. Constructions of Terrorism collects works from the leading scholars on terrorism from an array of disciplines—including communication, political science, sociology, global studies, and public policy—to establish appropriate research frameworks for understanding how we construct our understanding of terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTerrorismxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aal-qaeda.  acommunication.  acounterinsurgency.  acounterterrorism.  aglobal studies.  aglobal.  agovernment.  ainternational.  ajournalism.  alanguage.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern.  apolicy making.  apolicy.  apolitical science.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apublic policy.  areporting.  ascholarly.  ascholarship.  asociology.  aterrorism.  aterrorist groups.  aterrorist.  aviolence.1 aAsal, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlakeley, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurchill, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurchill, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChenoweth, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugan